@node introduction "Introduction"

@{b}Introduction@{ub}

@{i}200 years have passed since your last visit to Britannia. You return as the
Avatar to arrive on a scene of gruesome murder. Could the new-founded
organization known as "The Fellowship" which gains more and more followers be
involved in it? And what about this demonic creature called The Guardian who
seems to have an eye on every step you tread ...@{ui}

I'm very happy to present you the Amiga port of Exult, the role-playing game
engine which allows you to play Ultima 7 datafiles. Ultima 7 with its epic
storyline and vast world is still popular despite its age.

I had an eye on the Exult project from the very moment I heard of it. What made
this port finally feasible was Gabriele Greco's superb AmigaSDL port. Still,
it wasn't easy to build Exult, but it's done now so here it is for your enjoyment.

So if you are a role-playing game fan like myself and are tired of waiting for
Dafel: Bloodline, then put on the Avatar dress and step out onto the dusty and
dangerous roads of Britannia once more. Meet your old friends from Ultima 6, but
beware ... there's a foe. And he's strong. And he watches your every step ...

Rüdiger Hanke, July 2001
http://www.muenster.de/~tomjoad/

@endnode

@node required "System Requirements"

@{b}System Requirements@{ub}

In order to run Exult, you must have ...

   · a 68020 processor or better with FPU
   · AmigaOS 3.0 or later
   · a graphics card
   · CyberGraphX or Picasso96 with CGX emulation library installed

Optional are ...

   · AHI for sound effects
   · AMidi for MIDI music
   · OS3.5 or later for easier configuration

You'll also need the original Ultima 7 data files. Please notice that the
files in the Ultima 7 disk version are severely compressed, and you will
need to install the game under MS-DOS first before you can access the
required files. Alternately, the "Ultima Collection" CD-ROM contains the
unpacked game files.

Both the original "Black Gate" as well as the "Serpent Isle" add-on are
supported.

@endnode

@node installation "Installation"

@{b}Installation@{ub}

To install, copy the entire STATIC drawer of the original Ultima 7 game into
the empty BlackGate directory you'll find in the Exult directory after unpacking
the archive (note: copy the @{i}drawer@{ui} itself, not just the contents of the
drawer!).

If you own the add-on "Serpent Isle", copy its STATIC drawer into the SerpentIsle
directory.

If you downloaded the digital sound effects as well, please put the into the data
directory.

Basically, you can put the directories anywhere you like to, but then you'll have
to tell the game where to find them (see @{"Configuration" link configuration}.

@endnode

@node configuration "Configuration"

@{b}Configuration@{ub}

When you start the game, you have the chance to access the Setup screen where
you will be able to change some basic settings.

@{b}AmigaOS 3.1 and earlier@{ub}
If you want to change more settings or set some paths you have to edit the Exult.cfg
file in the Exult directory. See @{"part 3" link faq3} of the @{"FAQ" link faq} for
more information about doing this.

@{b}AmigaOS 3.5 and later@{ub}
If you double-click on the @{i}ExultPrefs@{ui} icon, the Amiga configuration
program will be loaded. This is currently still in beta, but it should work fine
already.

At the bottom of the window, you'll find three buttons:

@{i}Save & Launch@{ui} - saves the current configuration and starts Exult
@{i}Save@{ui}          - saves the current configuration and exits to Workbench
@{i}Cancel@{ui}        - exits to Workbench without saving the configuration

Click on the tabs to access the configuration pages. Currently there are ...

@{u}Games@{uu}
  Allows you to change the paths of the games to run with Exult. Currently, there are
  two subpages: Black Gate and Serpent Isle. Each presents you the following options:

  @{i}Data Path@{ui}   - set to the directory that contains the game's STATIC drawer
  @{i}SoundFX File@{ui}- the .flx file holding the sound effects. This file is not
                included in the distribution and must be downloaded from my
                or the Exult homepage seperately. There are different sound
                files for Black Gate and Serpent Isle.
  @{i}Keybindings@{ui} - the file with your custom keybindings. To switch back to the
                default keybindings, click the "Default" button next to it. See
                question 4.1 in the @{"FAQ" link faq4} for information on how to write your own
                keybindings.

@{u}Video@{uu}
  Settings for display and scaling.

  @{i}Resolution@{ui}  - the dimension of the game window. 320x200 is the original,
                but you can set it to anything you like. The chooser gadget gives you
                two preset resolutions (320x200 and 640x400); if you set it to "Other",
                you can enter your preferred resolution in the Width and Height gadgets
                next to it.
  @{i}Width@{ui}       - display width if Resolution is set to "Other".
  @{i}Height@{ui}      - display height if Resolution is set to "Other".
  @{i}Fullscreen@{ui}  - if checked, the game will open its own custom screen.
  @{i}No Fades@{ui}    - some screens are faded in and out. This option suppresses
                this fading.
  @{i}Enable Upscaling@{ui} - scales the original graphics to twice their size. Please
                note that the screen size will be doubled if you select this, so if
                you selected 640x400, then a 1280x800 window will be opened! There are
                several scaling strategies implemented. Display quality and speed decreases
                will depend on the chosen strategy.
  @{i}Scale Method@{ui} - here you can choose a scaling strategy. The best ones are
                probably SuperEagle and 2xSaI, but they're also very slow.
  @{i}Gamma Correction@{ui} - you can set gamma correction here, usually you won't
                need this.

@{u}Audio@{uu}
  @{i}Enable All Audio@{ui} - turns on all audio globally.
  @{i}Enable SFX@{ui}  - turns on sound effects. Note that you must have the sound
                pack installed which can be downloaded from my or the Exult
                homepage. Is always turned on if "all audio" is checked.
  @{i}Enable Speech@{ui}- turns on speech. Is always turned on if "all audio" is checked.
  @{i}Enable MIDI@{ui} - turns on MIDI. MIDI will only play if you have AMidi installed.
  @{i}AMidi Unit@{ui} - select the AMidi unit on which you'd like to play the music.

@{u}Gameplay@{uu}
  @{i}Skip Intro@{ui}  - skips the game intro that appears when you start a new game.
                It's recommended you watch it at least once.
  @{i}Skip Splash@{ui} - if selected, the Ultima 7 title screen and the intro will
                not appear and you will be taken directly to the game menu.
  @{i}Allow Cheats@{ui}- enable cheats. More information on cheats can be found
                in the @{"FAQ" link faq4}

@{u}Debug@{uu}
  @{i}Usecode@{ui}     - enables usecode debugging output. This should always be turned
                off since ordinary players won't give a damn about it.

@endnode

@node notes "Amiga Notes"

@{b}Amiga Notes@{ub}

@{i}Changed Keybindings:@{ui}

Those who have played Exult on other systems should be made aware that two
keybindings have been changed on the Amiga: you center the map with <Delete>
instead of <Home>, and the alternate Serpent Isle intro can be viewed using
Shift-F10 instead of F11.

@{i}Speed:@{ui}

The default configuration I provide with the Amiga version has been optimized
for slow Amigas - which does not mean it must necessarily run fast (although
it does here on my 060/50; I haven't tried with slower processors). It uses
the original Ultima 7 resolution of 320x200 pixels without scaling.

Owners of faster Amigas might want to try running the game in 640x400 resolution.
There is a scaling engine with various scaling strategies built into Exult.
Some are faster, some are slower but provide higher quality. You may want to
try several and see how they affect speed.

@{i}Cheats:@{ui}

In the default Amiga configuration, cheats are turned off.

@endnode

