@node faq5 "Frequent Questions: Exult Studio"

@{b}Frequent Questions Part 5: Exult Studio@{ub}

@{b}5.1. What is it?@{ub}
Exult Studio is a map-editor for Exult, allowing you to modify the map of a game and,
eventually, to create a completely new landscape for a new game.


@{b}5.2. Who came up with the cool name?@{ub}
Tristan


@{b}5.3. What do you need to run it?@{ub}
Currently, you need to be running Exult on X (Linux, Unix, etc.), with Exult set to run
in a window (not fullscreen). You also need the GTK+ library installed.


@{b}5.4. When will it be ported to other platforms?@{ub}
That depends on when someone volunteers to do the work :-) There are three issues:

GTK has to be ported to the platform. I think this is already true for Win32.
Exult Studio uses sockets to communicate with Exult. This also shouldn't be a problem
for Win32. X drag-n-drop is used to put new objects on the landscape. The 'drop' part
of this will have to be rewritten for Win32 Exult, OR, drag-n-drop could be an
enhancement to SDL someday.


@{b}5.5. How do you run it?@{ub}
You can run Exult Studio all by itself, but it isn't useful that way, as it uses Exult
as a server. What you really want to do is:

Put 'exult_studio.glade' in the Exult 'data' directory.
Be sure 'exult_studio' is in your path.
Run Exult.
Press 'alt-ctrl-m' to go into 'map-editor' mode. If all is set up correctly, exult_studio
will start up, and will have a list of files on the left side of its window.
You can also start up one or the other separately, and they'll reconnect:

If Exult isn't running, start it up. Then, in Exult Studio, use the 'File' menu to
choose the static directory (for the game you're playing).
If Exult Studio isn't running start it up with: exult_studio -x (path to dir containing
exult_studio.glade) -d (path to game directory)


@{b}5.6. What can you do at the moment?@{ub}
You can browse shapes in the main window.
You can drag a shape from the shape browser to Exult, and that object will be placed in
the game. (Note: Not all such objects are saved with the game yet; saving things like
buildings will be implemented soon.)
You can edit an 'egg' by double-clicking on it. An edit box should appear.
You can create a new 'egg' using the pull-down menu in Exult Studio. In the Egg edit box,
after you hit 'Apply', you'll be prompted to click in Exult where you want the egg to appear.
If editing a 'monster' egg, you can set the monster by dragging the shape from the
browser to the area that displays the monster.


@{b}5.7. What's next?@{ub}
The next things to be implemented are:

An NPC editor, similar to the one for Eggs (but with lots more stuff to set).
A simple object editor, that lets you modify an object's 'quality', 'quantity' and flags.
A 'save-map' function in Exult to save the whole map (not just the moveable objects that
'save-game' stores).


@{b}5.8. What's with this client/server stuff?@{ub}
A map-editor needs to provide the ability to display the game, place objects on the map,
and move objects around. That functionality is already in Exult, and it makes sense to
reuse it. So we could have made Exult a part of Exult Studio. However, Exult is already
a huge program, and is getting unwieldy to work on.

With this architecture, Exult Studio can have all the messy code for displaying/editing
dialog boxes, while Exult only needs a little bit of work to handle requests.

Also, I (Jeff) wanted to get a little experience programming with sockets:-)

